<i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Abenberg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of several places called Rabenberg, as for example in Saxony or Lower Saxony."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Rapoto","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Portuguese Duarte, Joao.","Portuguese: variant of   Raposo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Raposo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Antonio, Luis, Carlos, Jaime, Adriana, Alfonso, Americo, Ana, Eduardo, Fernando, Francisco.  Portuguese Joao, Duarte, Henrique, Paulo, Serafim, Vasco.","Portuguese: variant of   Raposa  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Rapoto II von Abenberg was born in 1122 as the son of Graf Rapoto I von Abenberg. He married Mathilda von Wettin in 1143. He died on 6 December 1172, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1122–6 December 1172":"1122–6. detsember 1172","1122–1172":"1122–1172","1120–1197":"1120–1197","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1138–1224":"1138–1224","1163–Male":"1163–Surnud","1167–Male":"1167–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1085–1145":"1085–1145","22 May 1145":"22. mai 1145","1110":"1110","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1163":"1163","1085":"1085","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","1138":"1138","6 December 1172":"6. detsember 1172","1224":"1224","about 1138":"umbes 1138","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1122":"1122","Abenberg, Germany":"Abenberg, Landkreis Roth, Bayern, Saksamaa","Nürnberg, Mittelfranken, Bavaria":"Nürnberg, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1122–6 December 1172":"1122–6. joulukuuta 1172","1122–1172":"1122–1172","1120–1197":"1120–1197","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1138–1224":"1138–1224","1163–Male":"1163–Kuollut","1167–Male":"1167–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1085–1145":"1085–1145","22 May 1145":"22. toukokuuta 1145","1110":"1110","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1163":"1163","1085":"1085","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","1138":"1138","6 December 1172":"6. joulukuuta 1172","1224":"1224","about 1138":"noin 1138","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1122":"1122","Abenberg, Germany":"Abenberg, Landkreis Roth, Bayern, Saksa","Nürnberg, Mittelfranken, Bavaria":"Nürnberg, Bayern, Saksa"},"fr":{"1122–6 December 1172":"1122–6 décembre 1172","1122–1172":"1122–1172","1120–1197":"1120–1197","1110–1152":